{{Single source|date=October 21, 2013}}  
{{Location map|Japan Fukushima Prefecture  
| label = Oguni Footslopes<br/>Kofun Group  
| position = top  
| mark = Red pog.svg  
| marksize = 10  
| relief = 1  
| width = 250  
| caption = {{Center|Location}}  
}}  
'''Oguni Footslopes Kofun Group''' (雄国山麓古墳群, Oguni-sanroku Kofun-gun) is a group of four burial mounds located in {{ill|Kitakata City|ja|喜多方市}}, {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県}}, Japan.  

== Overview ==  
The group comprises one square-shaped mound (方墳, hōfun) and three {{ill|Keyhole-shaped kofun|ja|前方後方墳}}. They are believed to have been constructed during the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代}}. The kofun were likely built by a third prominent clan in the Aizu Basin, following the clans that constructed the {{ill|Ikki Kofun Group|ja|一箕古墳群}} and the {{ill|Unai Aotsu Kofun Group|ja|宇内青津古墳群}}.  

== Kofun in the Group ==  
* **Fukasawa Kofun**  
* **Tanaka Funamori-yama Kofun**  
* **Jūkyūdan Kofun**  
* **Kannommori Kofun**  

== References ==  
* Hidehito Tsuji, *"The Origin of Tohoku Kofun Research: Aizu Otsukayama Kofun"* (Series: *Learning from Sites* 029), Shinseisha, 2006  

== Related Topics ==  
* {{ill|List of Kofun in Japan|ja|日本の古墳一覧}}  
* {{ill|Ikki Kofun Group|ja|一箕古墳群}}  
* {{ill|Unai Aotsu Kofun Group|ja|宇内青津古墳群}}  

{{Japanese-history-stub}}  
